<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-649-822  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 649 822.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  June 25 1990 v218 n26A p26(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Telecom in India: bringing order from chaos. (modernization oftelecommunications network)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rockwell, Mark.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>India's government and industry leaders are trying to modernizethe country's telecommunications system, which is not growing fastenough to accommodate user demands.andP;  The Department ofTelecommunications (DOT) was formed to oversee efforts to bringthe country's mostly analog-based system into line with moreadvanced technologies.andP;  As of Jul 1990, DOT leaders have succeededin keeping the Indian market closed to foreign telecommunicationssuppliers, but DOT's political prestige within the Indiangovernment is unstable.andP;  The current network still useselectromechanical exchanges and paper-insulated cables, and thereare only about 0.45 telephones per 100 people.andP;  Installation ofelectronic switches, multiplexing equipment, fiber optic trunkroutes and very small aperture terminals is scheduled for the nextfew years.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Very Small Aperture TerminalsTelecommunications ServicesCommunications EquipmentFiber opticsIndia.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>